{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"582"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/582"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.47,0.03,0.07,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107361"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5365"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11707"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107361"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner concerned about her risk of breast cancer. She has not had any recent weight loss or fevers, and has had no changes to her menstrual period. She has never had a mammogram. She performs breast self-examinations monthly and has never detected any anomaly. She has no significant medical history. She has a Mirena in-situ for contraception and takes no other regular medications. She has two children, the first of which she conceived at the age of 30-years. Her mother was diagnosed with breast cancer at the age of 48-years. Her paternal aunt was diagnosed with breast cancer at the age of 60-years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following screening regimens is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bi-ennial (two-yearly) mammograms from age 45","Annual mammograms from age 40","Annual clinical examination from age 40","Annual mammogram and ultrasound from age 45","Advise to adhere to population breast cancer screening"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn general, patients such as this woman who have a first-degree relative diagnosed with breast cancer aged \u0026lt;50 years old would be considered at a moderately increased risk of breast cancer. For women at moderate risk, RACGP guidelines make a conditional recommendation for mammographic screening\u003Cstrong\u003E at least\u003C/strong\u003E every 2 years from ages 40 to 74 - however, annual mammograms may be recommended (refer to \u0027Further information\u0027 in the RACGP guideline). Annual mammograms are not recommended for women with a single relative diagnosed with breast cancer over the age of 50 years, due to lack of clear evidence of benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, it is appropriate to start \u003Cstrong\u003Eannual mammograms \u003C/strong\u003Eaged 40 and above, and to consider referral to a specialist clinic for further evaluation and guidance regarding screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ebi-ennial mammograms\u003C/strong\u003E would be beneficial, annual mammograms are recommended in this patient according to current guidelines due to their moderate risk status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough this patient should be in regular touch with her GP and \u003Cstrong\u003Eclinical examination\u003C/strong\u003E is helpful, given her education and self-clinical examination, it is unlikely to provide significant benefit to perform annual clinical breast examinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual mammogram and ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in screening for breast cancer and is typically only performed if the patient presented with symptoms or a palpable breast lump needing further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current Australian government \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreast cancer screening program\u003C/strong\u003E is available for patients aged 50-74 at average or only slightly higher risk. For the average population, mammograms every 2 years during this time period is recommended, along with practicing breast awareness. This patient has a significant family history and needs annual mammogram screening from the age of 40 ideally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA thorough personalised risk calculation can be completed by both patients and doctors with iPrevent (which replaced the FRA-BOC score previously used). This online tool takes into account the full family history as well as other aspects of personal history including menarche, use of hormone replacement therapy, and smoking status. Another useful tool is the eviQ referral guidelines for cancer genetic assessment, which is an important consideration for breast cancer as well as other cancers including ovarian, colorectal, kidney, and prostate. Both resources are linked in the references.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with a family member \u003C50 diagnosed with breast cancer are at a moderately increased risk of breast cancer."],"references":["Early detection of cancers \u2013 Breast cancer. In: RACGP Red Book [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/breast-cancer","iPrevent Peter MacCallum Cancer Centre. [online]. 2024. Available at: https://iprevent.net.au","eviQ. General practitioner referral guidelines for cancer genetics assessment. June 7, 2023. Accessed March 25, 2024. Available at: https://www.eviq.org.au/cancer-genetics/referral-guidelines/1147-general-practitioner-referral-guidelines-for","Prevention and early detection of breast cancer. In: RACGP National Guide to Preventive Health Assessment for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander People [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/national-guide/chapter-15-prevention-and-early-detection-of-cance/prevention-and-early-detection-of-breast-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T07:46:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T07:47:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"582"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107361"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"c